@page "/"

<PageTitle>BlazorMap — Overview</PageTitle>

<h1>BlazorMap</h1>

<section class="demo-panel">
    <p>
        This solution ships a reusable <strong>BlazorMap</strong> Razor Class Library with provider-specific components
        (for example <code>BlazorLeafletMap</code>, <code>BlazorMapLibreMap</code>, and <code>BlazorMapboxMap</code>), each loading its vendor scripts from a CDN on first use.
        Components and geographic DTOs share the single <code>BlazorMap</code> namespace, so consuming apps only need <code>@("@using BlazorMap")</code>.
        The typed .NET API covers markers, vector shapes, GeoJSON, custom tiles, and map events where the underlying engine supports them.
    </p>
    <p>
        Use the navigation above for focused samples. This demo is a standalone Blazor WebAssembly app,
        so map interop runs entirely in the browser.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="demo-panel">
    <h2>Quick map</h2>
    <p>London, default OpenStreetMap tiles.</p>
    <div class="demo-map-wrap">
        <BlazorLeafletMap Height="280px" Options="@_opts" />
    </div>
</section>

<section class="demo-panel">
    <h2>Mapbox GL</h2>
    <p>
        The <code>BlazorMapboxMap</code> component uses Mapbox GL JS (not Leaflet). Open the
        <NavLink href="/mapbox">Mapbox demo</NavLink> and set <code>Mapbox:AccessToken</code> in
        <code>wwwroot/appsettings.json</code> to try it.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="demo-panel">
    <h2>MapLibre GL (free / open source)</h2>
    <p>
        <code>BlazorMapLibreMap</code> is a good choice when you want a WebGL slippy map without a Mapbox account.
        See the <NavLink href="/maplibre">MapLibre demo</NavLink> (default style works out of the box).
    </p>
</section>

<section class="demo-panel">
    <h2>Compared to other Blazor map libraries</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <strong>OpenLayers.Blazor</strong> — mature OpenLayers wrapper; OSM, Bing, Mapbox, SwissTopo,
            vector layers, GeoJSON, drawing, heatmaps. Strong choice when you need OGC services and projections.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>BlazorLeaflet</strong> — community Leaflet wrapper; simpler surface, historically alpha-style releases.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>BlazorBasics.Maps</strong> — unified API with Google or Leaflet backends for markers, routes, and clicks.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Telerik / Syncfusion / DevExpress</strong> — paid suites: layered tiles and vectors, rich zoom and
            pan modes, tooltips, marker clustering (Syncfusion), selection/highlight, scale and navigation UI, and
            (where providers allow) routing plus auto-fit to markers. See the <NavLink href="/enterprise">Enterprise</NavLink>
            demo for how this library mirrors a pragmatic subset without a subscription.
        </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        <strong>BlazorMap</strong> (this repo) keeps scope tight: small ES module bridges per provider, no vendor keys for the
        default Leaflet + OSM stack, and a C# surface you can extend. Routing like DevExpress requires your own geocoder/OSRM call; clustering can be added later via a Leaflet plugin.
    </p>
</section>

@code {
    private readonly LeafletMapDisplayOptions _opts = new()
    {
        Center = new LatLng(51.5074, -0.1278),
        Zoom = 12,
    };
}
